PAUL SOLMAN: So, then why isn't
it a good
thing that he's got Wilbur Ross,
Steve Mnuchin

38:06.217 --> 38:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and whoever else he gets from
Wall Street
in his administration?

38:09.154 --> 38:14.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM COHAN: They may turn out
to be just
what we're looking for.

38:14.292 --> 38:20.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if these Cabinet appointees
that he's
named, who have this kind of
experience about

38:20.365 --> 38:26.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
getting things done, and who
know how the
capital markets work, if they
can, all together,

38:26.204 --> 38:32.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do that, then I will be the
first one marching
at the front of the line to get
Donald Trump,

38:32.577 --> 38:39.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, reelected and say he
turned out
to be a lot better than anybody
thought.

38:39.984 --> 38:44.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But as somebody
who's known him
and reported on him, you're
skeptical?

38:44.489 --> 38:45.857 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WILLIAM COHAN: I'm skeptical.

38:45.890 --> 38:48.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm hoping he doesn't turn out
to be the guy
who cheats at golf.

38:48.393 --> 38:50.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: William D. Cohan,
thanks very
much.

38:50.361 --> 38:57.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM COHAN: Thanks for having
me.

38:57.202 --> 39:07.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another in
our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask interesting

39:07.478 --> 39:09.380 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people to share their passions.

39:09.414 --> 39:14.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from news media
critic and
New York University journalism
professor Jay

39:14.219 --> 39:15.954 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Rosen.

39:15.987 --> 39:20.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He runs the Web site
PressThink.org, and he
offers his views on the state of
journalism

39:20.858 --> 39:22.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the age of Facebook.

39:22.694 --> 39:24.462 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JAY ROSEN, Professor of
Journalism, New York
University: Twenty-five years
ago, we would

39:24.495 --> 39:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been in a studio somewhere
with 13 people
around.

39:28.600 --> 39:33.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're recording this with a
single cameraman
and his mom, who's holding the
microphone.

39:33.638 --> 39:39.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here, we have got our journalist
in another
city asking questions remotely.

39:39.410 --> 39:45.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's becoming easier to make
media, just at
the same time that the network
of news is

39:45.183 --> 39:52.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
expanding to include everyone
with a cell
phone all over the world.

39:52.724 --> 40:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, what I think we really
need is a press
that can sometimes say to us,
hey, you may

40:02.433 --> 40:06.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not think this is interesting,
but it's really
important.

40:06.871 --> 40:09.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Journalists have to give us that
kind of message
sometimes.

40:09.374 --> 40:16.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some people say the problem is
that people
are always listening to voices
that they already

40:16.814 --> 40:18.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
agree with on social media.

40:18.816 --> 40:25.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things journalists
are really struggling
with about Facebook is that it
has, in a way,

40:25.323 --> 40:29.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
replaced their relationship with
users of
the news.

40:29.694 --> 40:35.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead of going to their
favorite news site,
just find new stories in their
Facebook news

40:35.266 --> 40:36.467 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
feed.

40:36.501 --> 40:39.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That has given Facebook a huge
role in the
news system.

40:39.570 --> 40:45.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can't really ask Facebook the
kind of questions
we would ask an editor in chief,
because it

40:45.977 --> 40:47.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
doesn't have one.

40:47.745 --> 40:52.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you sign up for a Facebook
account, you
have to agree to this long list
that most

40:52.116 --> 40:53.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people don't read.

40:53.184 --> 40:55.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's thin legitimacy.

40:55.119 --> 40:58.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Thick legitimacy is when you
really understand
the deal.

40:58.489 --> 41:04.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, at some point, they may
realize that
thick legitimacy is what they
need to keep

41:04.395 --> 41:08.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
operating, because people trust
Facebook.

41:08.700 --> 41:12.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They advertise their life on
this platform.

41:12.337 --> 41:17.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, so, trust is actually a
huge part of
the Facebook business.

41:17.508 --> 41:22.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they don't think, in my
opinion, hard
enough about how to maintain
that trust.

41:22.847 --> 41:29.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's really important
for people to
understand that we're not going
to have serious

41:29.253 --> 41:33.458 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
journalism unless you choose it.

41:33.491 --> 41:39.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Choosing serious journalism is
related to
an even more serious choice we
have, which

41:39.197 --> 41:42.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is choosing to continue to be a
democracy.

41:42.567 --> 41:45.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Democracy is not a spectator
sport.

41:45.670 --> 41:47.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a participant thing.

41:47.739 --> 41:52.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Jay Rosen, and this
is my Brief
But Spectacular take on
journalism.

41:52.777 --> 41:57.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you can watch
additional
Brief But Spectacular episodes
