41:57.181 --> 41:59.684 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
site, PBS.org/NewsHour/Brief.

41:59.717 --> 42:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally
tonight: remembering
John Glenn, the Mercury
astronaut and former

42:05.723 --> 42:08.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.S. senator who died today at
95.

42:08.760 --> 42:10.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We start with this look back.

42:10.328 --> 42:12.163 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Godspeed, John Glenn.

42:12.196 --> 42:14.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: February 20,
1962.

42:14.832 --> 42:16.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Nine, eight.

42:16.334 --> 42:20.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: An Atlas
rocket fired Friendship
7 into space.

42:20.405 --> 42:26.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And over the next five hours,
John Glenn's
name was indelibly inscribed in
history, the

42:26.110 --> 42:29.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first American to orbit the
Earth circling
the globe three times.

42:29.981 --> 42:33.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN GLENN, NASA Astronaut: Zero
g and I feel
fine.

42:33.451 --> 42:34.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Capsule is turning around.

42:34.852 --> 42:36.554 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Oh, that view is tremendous.

42:36.587 --> 42:38.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: The honorable John Glenn.

42:38.322 --> 42:39.757 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

42:39.791 --> 42:41.793 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It was still
fresh in his
mind half-a-century later.

42:41.826 --> 42:48.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: For many, many
thousands of years,
people had looked up and
wondered.

42:48.232 --> 42:54.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They'd been curious about what
was up there.

42:54.172 --> 42:59.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, we must consider ourselves
among the
most fortunate of all
generations, for we

42:59.811 --> 43:03.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have lived at a time when the
dream became
a reality.

43:04.015 --> 43:08.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: John Glenn's
time began
in Ohio, where he was born and
raised.

43:08.853 --> 43:14.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He grew up to be a highly
decorated Marine
fighter pilot in World War II
and Korea.

43:14.091 --> 43:19.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as a military test pilot,
he set a transcontinental
speed record in 1957.

43:19.597 --> 43:23.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Then, space beckoned.

43:23.401 --> 43:30.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That same year, the Soviet Union
stunned the
world with Sputnik, the first
manmade satellite.

43:30.808 --> 43:38.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More Soviet successes followed,
while initial
U.S. unmanned launches met with
repeated failure.

43:38.883 --> 43:43.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Soviets also leaped ahead in
manned flight
with cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin
making the first

43:43.821 --> 43:48.926 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
orbital flight ever in April
1961.

43:48.960 --> 43:51.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Glenn was still training at that
point.

43:51.429 --> 43:56.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the first astronauts, the
Mercury 7,
he spoke of them at Cape
Canaveral in 2012.

43:56.367 --> 44:01.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: That was a real team
we put -- it
was put together back in those
days.

44:01.372 --> 44:07.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while we were competitors,
boy, were we
competitors to try and get the
different flights,

44:07.778 --> 44:12.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
never was there anything anymore
tight than
the brotherhood we had that
supported each

44:12.517 --> 44:14.385 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one of those flights.

44:14.418 --> 44:19.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Glenn's moment
came in early
1962, when he crammed his
silver-suited frame

44:19.290 --> 44:21.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into the tiny Friendship 7
capsule.

44:21.459 --> 44:23.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: We used to joke
about the spacecraft.

44:23.227 --> 44:27.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We said, you didn't climb -- you
didn't get
into it, you actually put it on.

44:27.298 --> 44:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was more like putting on
clothes.

44:29.066 --> 44:34.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was that small, because the
whole thing,
if you spread your arms out like
that, the

44:34.872 --> 44:37.608 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- you were touching both sides
of the spacecraft.

44:37.642 --> 44:42.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: People around
the world
watched, but few knew the danger
unfolding

44:42.547 --> 44:44.382 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
above.

44:44.415 --> 44:48.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The capsule's automated steering
system jammed
and ground controllers worried
the heat shield

44:48.185 --> 44:50.821 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was tearing away on reentry.

44:50.855 --> 44:55.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Glenn's life depended on that
shield, but
he told Judy Woodruff in 2012
his job was

44:55.860 --> 44:57.161 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to stay focused.

44:57.194 --> 44:59.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: You just keep right
on working
right on through it.

44:59.196 --> 45:02.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if something is going the
happen, the
worst thing you could do would
be panicky

45:02.366 --> 45:03.868 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in there.

45:03.901 --> 45:06.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I just kept on working as we
had trained,
and everything worked out OK.

45:06.604 --> 45:08.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: OK, does the capsule look
like it's OK?

45:08.973 --> 45:09.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Over.

45:09.974 --> 45:11.776 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Much more than
OK.

45:11.809 --> 45:17.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Glenn returned to Earth an
American hero,
feted with parades and elaborate
receptions.

45:17.448 --> 45:21.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President John F. Kennedy
presented him with
a NASA Service Medal, and, three
days later,

45:21.886 --> 45:23.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he addressed Congress.

45:23.754 --> 45:28.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: I am only too aware
of the tremendous
honor that is being show us at
this joint

45:28.559 --> 45:30.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
meeting of the Congress today.

45:30.328 --> 45:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has been a great experience
for all of
us on the program and for all
Americans, I

45:35.366 --> 45:37.168 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
guess, too.

45:37.201 --> 45:41.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I'm certainly glad to see
that pride in
our country and its
accomplishments are not

45:41.238 --> 45:42.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a thing of the past.

45:42.640 --> 45:46.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The space
program moved
on, and so did Glenn.

45:46.377 --> 45:51.482 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He resigned from NASA in 1964
and eventually
entered politics.

45:51.515 --> 45:57.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 1974, he was elected to the
U.S. Senate
from Ohio as a Democrat and
became chief author

45:57.722 --> 46:00.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Act.

46:00.458 --> 46:05.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 1984, he made a run for the
White House,
but he withdrew after poor
showings in the

46:05.596 --> 46:07.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
early Democratic primaries.

46:07.331 --> 46:10.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ultimately, he served four terms
in the Senate.

46:10.368 --> 46:12.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Three, two, one.

46:12.069 --> 46:17.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, in 1998,
in his final
months in office, he returned to
space on

46:17.742 --> 46:19.677 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
board the shuttle Discovery.

46:19.710 --> 46:26.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That earned him another first,
at 77, the
oldest person to fly into space.

46:26.117 --> 46:30.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After his Senate years, Glenn
and his wife,
Annie, worked to promote civics
education,

46:30.221 --> 46:35.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
establishing the John Glenn
College of Public
Affairs at Ohio State University
in Columbus.

46:36.027 --> 46:40.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But his abiding interest in
space was never
far away.

46:40.231 --> 46:44.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The aging astronaut sharply
criticized President
George W. Bush's decision to
phase out the

46:44.969 --> 46:46.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
space shuttle program.

46:46.303 --> 46:50.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MAN: Two, one, zero, and
liftoff, the final
liftoff of Atlantis.

46:50.708 --> 46:57.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The final
flight took place
in 2011, and Glenn voiced his
views in his

46:57.581 --> 46:59.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
"NewsHour" interview the next
year.

46:59.550 --> 47:03.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN GLENN: We do not have an
American spacecraft
on which we can go into space to
get our people

47:03.854 --> 47:08.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up there to the International
Space Station,
to do the research it was built
to do.

47:08.225 --> 47:10.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we spent over $100 billion
on that.

47:10.327 --> 47:14.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But we should have had a
continuity and a
program that would let us build,
research,

47:14.465 --> 47:18.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that the research we do up
there is of
benefit to everybody right here
on Earth.

47:18.069 --> 47:19.770 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

47:19.804 --> 47:21.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BOEHNER (R-OH), House
Minority Leader:
We will present a gold medal on
behalf of

47:21.472 --> 47:23.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the United States Congress to
the honorable
John Glenn.

47:24.008 --> 47:28.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Late in life,
he as still
being honored, receiving the
Congressional

47:28.212 --> 47:34.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gold Medal in 2011, along with
fellow astronauts
Buzz Aldrin, Neil Armstrong and
Michael Collins.

47:34.518 --> 47:40.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in 2012, he was awarded the
Presidential
Medal of Freedom, the nation's
highest civilian

47:40.925 --> 47:42.693 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
honor.

47:42.727 --> 47:48.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Glenn lived out his final
years in Ohio
after suffering a small stroke.

47:48.799 --> 47:52.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on the career and life
of John Glenn,
I am joined by science
correspondent Miles

47:52.136 --> 47:56.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
O'Brien, who came to know Glenn
through his
years of reporting on aviation.

47:56.107 --> 47:59.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Miles, it's the beginning of the
end of an
era.

47:59.577 --> 48:01.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It is, Hari.

48:01.645 --> 48:06.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't help but look at a guy
like that
and say, one of the last of the
great American

48:06.350 --> 48:08.219 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
heroes.

48:08.252 --> 48:14.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a guy who, whatever he
did, he succeeded
to levels few of us can ever
aspire to, and

48:14.658 --> 48:19.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
yet, all the while, was one of
the nicest
people you would ever want to
meet, despite

48:19.130 --> 48:21.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his relentless and competitive
nature.

48:21.832 --> 48:23.534 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's a hard mix.

48:23.567 --> 48:26.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he managed to do it, and he
managed to
do it really right to the end.

48:26.537 --> 48:27.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He never really quit.

48:27.705 --> 48:29.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He never retired.

48:29.073 --> 48:30.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He always had a mission.

48:30.241 --> 48:32.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You got to
know him personally.

48:32.076 --> 48:34.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You even flew with him in your
small plane?

48:34.111 --> 48:36.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes, I cooked up
a scheme for
a story.

48:36.714 --> 48:40.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had met him during the 1998
flight on the
shuttle, when I had the
opportunity to cover

48:40.785 --> 48:45.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him and have no less than Walter
Cronkite
as my co-anchor on CNN.

48:45.055 --> 48:47.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I consider myself very lucky to
have had that
experience.

48:47.758 --> 48:52.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, some years later, we were
doing a story
on technology and aviation, and
I got the

48:52.296 --> 48:56.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
idea in my head that it would be
kind of fun
to see what Senator Glenn
thought about the

48:56.867 --> 48:57.968 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
technology.

48:58.002 --> 48:59.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It happened to be in the
aircraft I owned
at the time.

48:59.804 --> 49:05.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I flew it to Columbus, and I had
John Glenn
get in my airplane and fly with
me.

49:05.342 --> 49:09.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have got to tell you,
Hari, I have never
had a more nervous landing in my
life.

49:09.580 --> 49:12.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But as the term in aviation is,
I greased
it.

49:12.683 --> 49:15.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he was -- he could not have
been more
complimentary to me.

49:15.286 --> 49:19.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was the nicest passenger you
could ever
hope for, and yet the most
intimidating at

49:19.290 --> 49:21.025 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the same time.

49:21.058 --> 49:24.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He's almost a
time capsule
in a way of the relations
between America

49:24.195 --> 49:28.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the world, and what he meant
to the space
program, what he meant to
aviation at the

49:28.165 --> 49:30.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time, especially in the context
of the Cold
War.

49:30.034 --> 49:31.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Absolutely, Hari.

49:31.802 --> 49:37.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you think of NASA and what
the space
program is all about, it was
kind of a Cold

49:37.107 --> 49:40.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
War projection of soft power of
the United
States.

49:40.144 --> 49:42.913 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he was the perfect poster
boy for that.

49:42.947 --> 49:50.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was everything that we -- was
considered
the ideal in this country,
small-town ethics,

49:50.855 --> 49:56.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you know, handsome guy, the
whole -- really
central casting kind of thing.

49:56.260 --> 50:01.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was the guy, somewhat at
least, with some
drama, depicted in "The Right
Stuff" in the

50:01.298 --> 50:06.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
mid-'80s, sort of the, for lack
of a better
term, Goody Two-Shoes of the
Mercury 7.

50:06.971 --> 50:10.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While the rest of them might
have been out
carousing late into the night,
he was with

50:10.674 --> 50:17.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his longtime wife, who actually
he met first
in preschool, Annie, and lived a
much more

50:17.982 --> 50:19.750 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
quiet experience in life.

50:19.783 --> 50:21.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And he went on
to serve
after as well.

50:21.986 --> 50:24.088 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: He did, indeed.

50:24.121 --> 50:29.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The chapters of his life are
amazing, Marine
Corps fighter pilot in Korea
with numerous

50:29.860 --> 50:39.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kills to his record, set a
cross-country transcontinental
supersonic record as a Marine
test pilot in

50:39.236 --> 50:44.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the '50s, goes on to be the
Mercury 7, then
has this brief chapter as the
president of

50:44.642 --> 50:49.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Royal Crown Cola, then gets into
politics
for 24 years, and then goes on
to build this

50:49.847 --> 50:53.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
amazing public policy school at
Ohio State
University.

50:53.617 --> 50:58.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Each chapter, he just rose to
the absolute
top level, and made it always
look effortless,

50:58.822 --> 51:00.257 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at least as far as I could see.

51:00.291 --> 51:02.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

51:02.059 --> 51:05.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even as we saw in the clips
there, he
was still advocating for a more
active role

51:05.229 --> 51:07.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the space program.

51:07.064 --> 51:10.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You know, when
George Bush
announced the retirement of the
space shuttle,

51:10.801 --> 51:13.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he was calling me a lot.

51:13.537 --> 51:19.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he was advocating, in a very
forceful
and clear way, for the United
States still

51:19.043 --> 51:22.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
having the ability to carry its
own astronauts
to space.

51:22.346 --> 51:23.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he wasn't going to let that
go.

51:23.514 --> 51:24.915 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He was very upset about it.

51:24.949 --> 51:28.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was well into his 80s at this
point, but
he was still in the game.

51:28.585 --> 51:30.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right.

51:30.187 --> 51:32.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know if we have footage,
or if it's
a shot of you and him in a
plane.

51:32.856 --> 51:35.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's see if we can show that to
our audience
as well.

51:35.492 --> 51:39.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, while we're
